desc: Based on its profile as a small relatively remote gmina seat in Ciechanów County (outside major urban‐suburban zones) – comparable to other Masovian rural communities that fall into the midrange of graduate attainment – the share of university‐educated residents in Glinojeck gmina would best be classed as Medium.

Based on its rural‐small‐town character in the otherwise industrial yet mixed‐development Śląskie region Koszęcin (Lubliniecki powiat) would be expected to have a roughly average share of university graduates.  
Answer: Medium

Based on its rural character yet proximity to the urbanized Gliwice/Katowice area—similar to other Polish villages we rated as “Medium”—I would classify Ligota Łabędzka’s share of tertiary‐educated residents as:  
Medium.

Based on its location in Katowice – a major Silesian metropolitan centre with several universities (University of Silesia Silesian University of Technology Medical University of Silesia etc.) – Brynów-Osiedle Zgrzebnioka will have an above-average share of university graduates (though not on par with Warsaw proper).  I therefore classify it as High.

Based on its location – a small village in Jarosławski powiat in the relatively less‐developed Podkarpackie province – but noting that most rural Polish localities score around “Medium” in tertiary‐education share I would classify ulica Wietlin Laszki as:

Answer: Medium
Based on its profile as a small rural‐gmina seat in Kujawsko-Pomorskie (outside major metro commuter belts) Dębowa Łąka’s share of university graduates is best classed as Medium.

Based on its position as a small village in a largely rural gmina just outside Toruń—whose overall tertiary‐attainment (≈23 %) is around the Polish average—and by analogy with similarly situated localities (Rynarcice Ramsowo etc.) Toporzysko’s share of university‐educated residents would be classified as Medium.

Based on its location in a predominantly rural county (Włocławski) within the Kujawsko-Pomorskie province—which overall shows average tertiary‐education rates in Poland—and by analogy with similar rural districts (e.g. in Dolnośląskie or Warmińsko-Mazurskie) that we’ve classified as “Medium” I would infer that Wieniec Zalesie falls into the Medium category.

Based on its small‐village character within the Konin peri-urban zone—and by analogy to similarly sized Polish rural localities (e.g. Niwiski Ramsowo)—we’d place Daninów at the “Medium” level of highly educated (university‐graduate) share.

Based on its being a small rural village in Pilski county (Wielkopolskie)—a part of Poland where higher‐education uptake is modest outside the few local towns—and by analogy with other Polish rural localities (e.g. Rynarcice Ramsowo Niwiski) that all struck a “Medium” level Dziembowo most plausibly falls into the Medium class. Answer: Medium

Answer: Medium

Chojno is a small village in the Gmina Wronki (Szamotulski county) of the Wielkopolskie voivodeship – a moderately prosperous primarily rural area outside larger urban centres. Based on comparable village‐level locations in Poland’s western and central regions (e.g. Rynarcice in Dolnośląskie or Ramsowo in Warmińsko‐Mazurskie both rated “Medium”) and given its distance from a major university hub the share of university‐educated residents is likely around the national rural average placing it in the “Medium” class.

Based on the village’s location in a predominantly rural part of Grodzisk Wielkopolski County (Wielkopolskie Voivodeship)—a region with average‐to‐slightly‐below‐average tertiary attainment relative to Poland as a whole—and given the benchmarking of similar rural localities in the dataset the share of university graduates in Kotusz is best classified as “Medium.”

Based on its location in a sparsely populated largely rural part of Warmińsko-Mazurskie – similar in character to Ramsowo (which we classified as Medium) – Radzie (Gmina Wydminy Giżycki powiat) would likewise fall into the Medium bucket.

Based on its status as a working‐class residential district of a mid‐sized regional capital (Szczecin) with a share of tertiary‐educated residents near the national average rather than the very high levels seen in Warsaw I’d classify Dąbie (Szczecin) as:  
Answer: Medium

Based on its location—a small rural settlement in Zachodniopomorskie with socio-economic and educational levels broadly in line with other Polish villages that we’ve rated “Medium”—Bonin would likewise fall into the Medium category.

Based on its location—a small rural locality in Podlaskie with no immediate proximity to a major urban center—and by analogy with similar Polish villages (e.g. Rynarcice Niwiski Ramsowo) the share of university‐educated residents is likely in the “Medium” range. Answer: Medium

Based on its location within a major university city (Wrocław) but not being one of the most central or elite districts Popowice would be expected to have a relatively strong share of university‐educated residents—placing it in the “High” class.

Based on the rural‐suburban character of Szczedrzyk in the Ozimek district (Opolskie Voivodeship) and by analogy with similarly sized Polish villages (which we’ve classified as “Medium”) the share of university‐educated residents there is best placed in the Medium category.

Based on its rural low‐density profile in Sieradz County (Łódzkie) and by analogy with similar Polish villages (e.g. Rynarcice Niwiski Ramsowo all rated “Medium”) Wola Będkowska would likewise be classed as: Medium.

Based on its location in an urban district of Łódź (a regional university centre though below Warsaw’s level) Stary Widzew’s share of university‐educated residents is expected to be above average but not top-tier.  
Answer: High

Based on its rural‐village character in central Poland (a small settlement within Łowicki district with no strong urban/suburban influence) and by analogy with the other Polish “village” examples (which consistently fell into the Medium category) I would classify Skaratki’s share of university‐educated residents as: Medium.

Based on its very rural forest‐dominated setting (a national park) in the Chojnicki district – which shows below‐average tertiary‐educated shares in Pomerania – we’d classify this location’s proportion of university graduates as Medium.

Based on its profile as a small village in the rural hinterland of Gniew (Tczewski county) and by analogy with other Polish rural localities in Pomorskie Szprudowo most likely falls into the Medium class for share of university‐educated residents.
Based on its location – a small village in the commuter belt of the Tricity but still essentially rural – Warzno would fall into the “Medium” class for share of university‐educated residents.

Based on its status as a small village in a largely rural gmina on the outskirts of Słupsk (a mid‐sized city without a major university campus) and by analogy with similarly positioned Polish villages (e.g. Ramsowo Niwiski Rynarcice—all rated “Medium”) Ochodza’s share of university‐educated residents is best classified as:  
Answer: Medium

Based on Netta Druga’s location—a small tourism-oriented village in the relatively under-educated Podlaskie region with limited local access to higher-education institutions and substantial out-migration of youth for university—I would classify its share of university graduates as Low.

Based on its profile as a small village in Zielonogórski (Lubuskie)—close enough to the university city of Zielona Góra to attract some graduates but still a predominantly rural district—its share of university‐educated residents most closely matches the “Medium” benchmark.

Based on its rural character in one of Poland’s less‐educated voivodeships (Świętokrzyskie) but noting that most Polish villages still tend to fall into the medium bracket rather than the lowest one I would classify Gruszka Zagnańsk Kielecki as:

Answer: Medium

Based on its location within the city of Tarnów (a mid‐sized regional centre in Małopolskie) and the presence of tertiary‐level institutions and professional employment—yet not on the scale of Warsaw or Kraków—I would classify Mościce (powiat miasta Tarnów) as having a “High” share of university‐educated residents.
Based on its rural‐suburban profile and benchmarked against similar Polish districts Ostrężnica most likely falls into the Medium class.

Based on its profile as a small‐town/village community in the Kraków commuter belt—with neither large university campuses nor pronounced academic‐professional clusters right on site—Kwaczała most likely falls into the “Medium” bracket for share of highly educated residents.

Based on Podgórze’s location in central Kraków (a major university city) its strong student and academic presence and ongoing gentrification the share of university‐educated residents would be classified as: Very High.
Based on Trenčín region’s above‐national‐average but still modest tertiary graduation rates (roughly in the low‐20% range) Bobot would most likely fall into the “Medium” class.

Based on its status as a large university city’s residential district (though not the city centre) and comparing to our Czech Polish and Hungarian benchmarks Južné Mesto in Košice IV most likely falls into the “Medium” category.

Based on Prague 10’s urban university‐rich population within the capital region the share of tertiary graduates there aligns with the “Very High” benchmark.  
Answer: Very High

Based on its proximity to the city of Zlín (home to Tomas Bata University) the largely commuter‐based population and the higher overall regional development in Zlínský kraj compared with more rural Czech locations Podřevnická in Želechovice nad Dřevnicí would be assessed at a “Medium” level of university‐educated share.

Based on Gyömrő’s proximity to Budapest and its role as a commuter‐town in Pest County—where educational attainment typically runs above the Hungarian national average but still below that of a major city centre—the share of university‐educated residents here is best classified as High.
Based on its status as a small rural village in Fejér County—comparable to other low‐attainment Hungarian localities—I’d classify Seregélyes’s share of university‐educated adults as Low.

Based on Tata’s status as a small regional town in one of Hungary’s more developed high‐GDP‐per‐capita counties (Komárom-Esztergom) its proximity to the industrial city of Tatabánya and county‐level tertiary attainment (~17 % in recent censuses which is above the Hungarian rural average but below Budapest) I would classify the share of university‐educated residents in 2890 Tata as “High.”

Based on its rural setting in Somogy (a less‐developed largely agricultural county) and by analogy with similarly sized Hungarian villages (e.g. Baktalórántháza Varsád) the share of tertiary‐educated residents in Mezőcsokonya would be classified as Low.

Based on Nógrádsipek’s rural setting in the economically weaker Nógrád county—comparable to other small Hungarian settlements (e.g. Baktalórántháza in Szabolcs-Szatmár-Bereg or Varsád in Tolna) that we rated “Low”—we would likewise assign Nógrádsipek a “Low” level of university-educated population.

Based on Soltvadkert’s location in a predominantly rural lower‐development county (Bács‐Kiskun) its small‐town character and regional education profiles the share of university‐educated residents is best classified as Low.

Based on Murony’s rural setting in Békés County—characterized by low urbanisation an agriculture‐centered local economy and relatively limited access to higher‐education institutions—the share of university‐educated residents is judged to fall into the “Low” category.
